Oh, wow, it's beautiful.

237
00:15:16,149 --> 00:15:17,582
You like it?
I love it.

238
00:15:17,650 --> 00:15:19,083
Good. Here, allow me.

239
00:15:20,086 --> 00:15:21,075
Gosh.

240
00:15:22,555 --> 00:15:23,988
You shouldn't have.

241
00:15:24,057 --> 00:15:25,183
I wanted to.

242
00:15:25,792 --> 00:15:30,024
Hey, hey,
are you crying?
No, I'm too tough to cry.

243
00:15:30,129 --> 00:15:31,118
Oh.

244
00:15:31,197 --> 00:15:34,598
Though my nasal passages
do become congested
when I'm sad.

245
00:15:34,801 --> 00:15:37,497
Oh, don't be sad.
It's your birthday. Hmm?

246
00:15:38,137 --> 00:15:40,230
Oh, I wish I could
celebrate with you tonight.

247
00:15:40,306 --> 00:15:42,297
I just have to go out of town
for a few days.

248
00:15:42,508 --> 00:15:43,497
Really?

249
00:15:43,576 --> 00:15:46,511
Yes, I just have
some business to take care of.

250
00:15:47,180 --> 00:15:49,204
But we'll celebrate
when I get back, all right?
Okay.

251
00:15:51,249 --> 00:15:53,308
Thank you so much
for the present.
It's beautiful.

252
00:15:53,385 --> 00:15:54,909
I'll think about you
whenever I wear it.

253
00:15:58,056 --> 00:15:59,614
You didn't tell me
it was your birthday!

254
00:15:59,691 --> 00:16:01,454
I'll take you
for a magnificent dinner.

255
00:16:01,526 --> 00:16:03,323
We'll go
to a great restaurant.
Really?

256
00:16:03,428 --> 00:16:07,387
Do you enjoy
the McNuggets thing?

257
00:16:08,467 --> 00:16:11,698
What about Indian food?
Do you like spicy food?

258
00:16:11,937 --> 00:16:13,700
No, no, it's okay.

259
00:16:13,772 --> 00:16:15,706
I don't really have
much of an appetite.

260
00:16:15,874 --> 00:16:18,638
But you will when
they bring out the prawns
in hydrochloric acid.

261
00:16:18,710 --> 00:16:20,405
It's fantastic, Sondra.

262
00:16:21,713 --> 00:16:23,613
What's the matter?

263
00:16:23,682 --> 00:16:25,615
What,
are you thinking of Peter?
No.

264
00:16:26,250 --> 00:16:27,547
I don't know, it's just...

265
00:16:27,618 --> 00:16:30,086
I wouldn't be surprised
if he asked me to marry him
one day, you know?

266
00:16:30,154 --> 00:16:32,782
You come
from an Orthodox family.

267
00:16:32,857 --> 00:16:35,257
Would they accept
a serial killer?

268
00:16:36,060 --> 00:16:37,721
That's an expensive present.

269
00:16:38,863 --> 00:16:42,230
The Lymans are so wealthy.
Yes.

270
00:16:42,299 --> 00:16:44,062
It was almost
too extravagant.

271
00:16:44,468 --> 00:16:47,631
I'd better get ready.
I still haven't found
my millionaire yet.

272
00:16:51,008 --> 00:16:53,476
Oh, God, Sondra, what a mess!

273
00:16:55,679 --> 00:16:57,010
It's starting to add up
against him.

274
00:16:57,081 --> 00:16:58,844
Bits and scraps
are coming together.

275
00:16:58,916 --> 00:17:00,315
God, it's you!

276
00:17:00,518 --> 00:17:03,111
I sensed
you were falling in love.
I escaped again.

277
00:17:03,219 --> 00:17:06,848
It's just circumstantial junk,
you know. A coincidence
here and there.

278
00:17:06,923 --> 00:17:08,948
Too much smoke
not to be fire.

279
00:17:09,059 --> 00:17:11,391
Look, I'm sure
you've been wrong
plenty of times.

280
00:17:11,461 --> 00:17:12,621
Not wrong here.

281
00:17:12,695 --> 00:17:16,153
Though I agree
you haven't got enough
to pull the trigger yet.

282
00:17:16,332 --> 00:17:18,562
If you act prematurely,
not only does he walk,

283
00:17:18,635 --> 00:17:21,729
your professional credibility
is wrecked,
sometimes for good.

284
00:17:21,805 --> 00:17:23,739
Oh, I'm sure you want him
to be guilty.

285
00:17:23,840 --> 00:17:25,865
You know, that way you get
your last big scoop.

286
00:17:25,975 --> 00:17:27,374
I'm beginning to fade.

287
00:17:27,444 --> 00:17:29,275
Sondra, don't let me down!

288
00:17:29,345 --> 00:17:31,438
I wish you'd fade for good!

289
00:17:31,614 --> 00:17:32,774
Get out of my life!

290
00:17:32,849 --> 00:17:34,282
I'm not
cut out for this.

291
00:17:34,350 --> 00:17:36,875
I should be
flossing molars for a living.

292
00:17:37,921 --> 00:17:40,616
The bread is... You know,
I can make a meal
just with the bread.

293
00:17:40,689 --> 00:17:42,589
I can do a whole meal,
just nothing but bread.

294
00:17:42,791 --> 00:17:45,624
If I ate that much bread,
I'd be 20 pounds heavier.

295
00:17:45,694 --> 00:17:47,559
See,
I never gain an ounce,

296
00:17:47,629 --> 00:17:51,759
because, you know,
my anxiety acts like aerobics.

297
00:17:52,034 --> 00:17:53,433
So I get the exercise.

298
00:17:54,269 --> 00:17:56,965
Thanks for taking me out
for my birthday, Sidney.

299
00:17:57,072 --> 00:17:59,563
Well, you know,
you're the daughter
that I never had.

300
00:17:59,641 --> 00:18:01,632
Oh, that's so...
No, no, I'm kidding.
I'm kidding.

301
00:18:01,710 --> 00:18:03,109
'Cause I never wanted
to have kids.

302
00:18:03,512 --> 00:18:05,810
I didn't.
Because you have kids,
what is it?

303
00:18:06,115 --> 00:18:08,913
You know, you're nice
to them, you bring
them up, you suffer,

304
00:18:08,984 --> 00:18:10,474
you take care of them

305
00:18:10,552 --> 00:18:14,989
and then they grow up
and they accuse you
of having Alzheimer's.

306
00:18:15,524 --> 00:18:17,115
Could you
ever live in London?

307
00:18:18,693 --> 00:18:20,160
Could I live
in London? No.

308
00:18:20,228 --> 00:18:22,423
And I love London.
Don't get me wrong,
I love London,

309
00:18:22,497 --> 00:18:24,692
but, you know,

310
00:18:24,999 --> 00:18:28,730
apart from
the language problem,
I can't take the driving.

311
00:18:28,803 --> 00:18:31,863
Because it, you know,
it's on the wrong side,
and I...

312
00:18:32,306 --> 00:18:34,103
Every time
I drive a car here,

313
00:18:34,175 --> 00:18:36,439
I'm convinced
I'm going to die in a crash.

314
00:18:37,778 --> 00:18:38,767
Sidney!

315
00:18:38,946 --> 00:18:39,935
What's the matter?

316
00:18:40,581 --> 00:18:41,878
It's Peter.

317
00:18:41,949 --> 00:18:43,007
You said
Peter was out of town.

318
00:18:43,084 --> 00:18:44,915
Well, that's
what he told me.

319
00:18:45,486 --> 00:18:46,475
Come on.

320
00:18:46,654 --> 00:18:47,916
What do you mean, come on?

321
00:18:47,989 --> 00:18:50,150
I ordered prawns.

322
00:18:50,358 --> 00:18:52,451
Just pay, all right?
Just pay.

323
00:18:52,727 --> 00:18:54,819
What do you mean, pay?
All I do is...

324
00:18:54,895 --> 00:18:56,988
Fine, it's her birthday.

325
00:19:00,267 --> 00:19:01,325
Come on.

326
00:19:01,735 --> 00:19:03,862
Maybe he's got
another woman on the side,

327
00:19:03,970 --> 00:19:06,939
and he likes you,
but he's sexually
attracted to her.

328
00:19:07,240 --> 00:19:08,400
Thanks, Sidney.

329
00:19:08,475 --> 00:19:10,102
Well, why doesn't he have
his chauffeur?

330
00:19:10,177 --> 00:19:12,145
I don't know,
whatever he's doing,
he must want it to be secret.

331
00:19:49,114 --> 00:19:51,446
Oh, I told you
he went the other way!

332
00:19:51,917 --> 00:19:53,509
Can we go home, please?

333
00:19:53,586 --> 00:19:55,349
It's starting to rain.

334
00:19:55,421 --> 00:19:57,821
I can't believe
he lied to me.

335
00:19:58,057 --> 00:20:01,720
Maybe he's doing
something that he's ashamed
to tell you about.

336
00:20:01,794 --> 00:20:05,662
Maybe he belongs to
one of those clubs, or he's
a cross-dresser or something.

337
00:20:05,731 --> 00:20:07,891
Or maybe
he does folk dancing.

338
00:20:07,999 --> 00:20:10,433
Oh, I'm sure
it's probably something
that when he tells me,

339
00:20:10,501 --> 00:20:12,526
I'll just feel foolish
for thinking he lied.

340
00:20:12,604 --> 00:20:15,835
I'm sure. You know,
not everything in
this world is sinister.

341
00:20:15,907 --> 00:20:17,670
You know,
just practically everything.

342
00:20:17,742 --> 00:20:20,575
That Indian food
made me sick.

343
00:20:21,145 --> 00:20:24,137
You hardly touched
your cobra salad.
How can you be sick?

344
00:20:24,415 --> 00:20:26,178
Help!

345
00:20:26,251 --> 00:20:28,913
A woman's been strangled!

346
00:20:29,420 --> 00:20:33,823
Help!
A woman's been strangled!
Help, call the police!

347
00:20:33,891 --> 00:20:35,882
Somebody call the police!
There's been a murder!

348
00:20:35,960 --> 00:20:37,257
There's been
a murder upstairs.

349
00:20:37,328 --> 00:20:38,317
Help!

350
00:20:38,429 --> 00:20:40,420
Have you got a phone?
Have you got a phone?
Call the police.

351
00:20:40,498 --> 00:20:43,296
Could it be the Tarot Killer?
They found a Tarot card.
It's him.

352
00:20:43,368 --> 00:20:44,766
I can't believe it!
She lives in this building.

353
00:20:44,835 --> 00:20:46,996
It's him again.
They found the Tarot card.

354
00:20:48,639 --> 00:20:51,472
Elizabeth Gibson,
another short-haired brunette.

355
00:20:51,708 --> 00:20:54,268
We should have
gone to the police earlier.

356
00:20:54,378 --> 00:20:57,404
Well, you know...
You said that they
wouldn't believe us

357
00:20:57,481 --> 00:20:59,676
and they may not.

358
00:21:00,050 --> 00:21:03,508
Sidney, it's about time
we show my story to
a real newspaperman.

359
00:21:04,655 --> 00:21:05,986
By real, you mean what?

360
00:21:06,156 --> 00:21:07,248
One that's living.

361
00:21:07,691 --> 00:21:10,455
<i>Vivian's father has a friend
that works at The Observer.</i>

362
00:21:12,129 --> 00:21:14,427
Well, it's very vivid
and rather shocking,

363
00:21:14,498 --> 00:21:17,331
and there are some
genuine circumstantial
bits of evidence.

364
00:21:17,401 --> 00:21:21,131
But let me give you a lesson
in professional journalism.

365
00:21:22,338 --> 00:21:25,933
No newspaper should
or would ever run this story.

366
00:21:26,676 --> 00:21:28,166
What? Why?

367
00:21:28,811 --> 00:21:31,939
It would be
fatally irresponsible
and libelous.

368
00:21:32,615 --> 00:21:35,550
All you have here
are a number
of titillating speculations.

369
00:21:36,419 --> 00:21:40,116
Flamboyant theories that
tarnish a man, and a
well-known figure at that,

370
00:21:40,189 --> 00:21:42,749
without a single shred
of substantial proof.

371
00:21:43,893 --> 00:21:46,054
So his mother
was a short-haired brunette.

372
00:21:46,195 --> 00:21:48,026
So he came late
for a poker game

373
00:21:48,097 --> 00:21:51,658
and said he was going away
on a business trip
and he got caught lying.

374
00:21:51,967 --> 00:21:56,734
Yes, but who keeps
a Tarot deck under
a French horn?

375
00:21:57,540 --> 00:22:01,566
It's not against the law
to own a Tarot deck,
or keep it wherever you like.

376
00:22:03,011 --> 00:22:05,309
You'd look
pretty foolish in court
with your accusations,

377
00:22:05,380 --> 00:22:07,007
and that's
where you'll wind up.

378
00:22:07,382 --> 00:22:10,374
Because he'd have no choice
but to sue you
and the newspaper,

379
00:22:10,452 --> 00:22:11,578
and he'd win.

380
00:22:12,020 --> 00:22:13,385
And to go to the police?

381
00:22:14,222 --> 00:22:15,416
I'll come to that.

382
00:22:15,490 --> 00:22:18,653
But first let me
continue my tedious
professorial lecture.

383
00:22:20,428 --> 00:22:22,555
Vivian's dad and I
go way back.

384
00:22:22,964 --> 00:22:25,057
He said you were
a journalism student.

385
00:22:25,834 --> 00:22:26,823
Hmm.

386
00:22:27,869 --> 00:22:29,461
You talk about getting a tip.

387
00:22:29,671 --> 00:22:31,502
Okay, you won't
disclose your source,

388
00:22:31,573 --> 00:22:34,700
but what you have done
is let your imagination
run wild.

389
00:22:34,842 --> 00:22:35,900
No, no.

390
00:22:35,976 --> 00:22:39,537
What if I told you
that my source happened
to be a certain Joe Strombel?

391
00:22:40,180 --> 00:22:42,080
The late Joe Strombel?
Yep.

392
00:22:42,149 --> 00:22:44,583
You mean, before he died
he gave a student reporter

393
00:22:44,651 --> 00:22:46,983
a major story
and didn't follow
it up himself?

394
00:22:47,054 --> 00:22:49,750
We didn't say
it was before he died.

395
00:22:50,891 --> 00:22:52,256
What?
No, it...

396
00:22:52,326 --> 00:22:53,884
He got the story
before he died,

397
00:22:53,961 --> 00:22:56,395
and then he died
before he could follow it up.

398
00:22:58,132 --> 00:23:01,397
Well,
why did he give it to you?
He didn't know he was dying.

399
00:23:01,702 --> 00:23:02,862
I don't buy it.

400
00:23:02,936 --> 00:23:04,494
I knew Joe Strombel well.

401
00:23:04,838 --> 00:23:07,170
If he'd had a tip
that he considered reliable,

402
00:23:07,808 --> 00:23:09,833
he would certainly
have pursued it himself,

403
00:23:09,910 --> 00:23:11,809
from the grave,
if necessary.

404
00:23:13,012 --> 00:23:15,810
What about how Peter
was in the neighborhood

405
00:23:15,882 --> 00:23:17,907
the night
the murder was committed?

406
00:23:19,118 --> 00:23:21,484
I realize as a student
how exciting it must have been

407
00:23:21,554 --> 00:23:24,182
to think that you were onto
something so spectacular.

408
00:23:24,323 --> 00:23:25,790
Hey, she is onto something!

409
00:23:25,858 --> 00:23:27,917
This kid is a bloodhound.
Look at her!

410
00:23:27,994 --> 00:23:31,521
She could sell the story
to any tabloid in town.

411
00:23:32,165 --> 00:23:33,154
Hmm.

412
00:23:34,100 --> 00:23:37,228
Now that I've preached
on the realities
of accurate reporting,

413
00:23:37,303 --> 00:23:41,330
I want to tell you
how catastrophic
for everybody involved

414
00:23:41,407 --> 00:23:43,534
it would have been
if you had, say, taken

415
00:23:43,609 --> 00:23:46,737
the results
of your investigation
to a tabloid.

416
00:23:48,080 --> 00:23:51,640
Today, the police
have apprehended
the Tarot Card Serial Killer.

417
00:23:52,250 --> 00:23:55,014
And it most assuredly
is not Peter Lyman.

418
00:23:55,520 --> 00:23:56,748
What?

419
00:23:56,822 --> 00:23:59,916
Every paper in town
is going to press
with it as we speak.

420
00:24:00,792 --> 00:24:04,523
It was a handyman
named Henry Banks
who has confessed.

421
00:24:05,230 --> 00:24:08,393
Banks is a delusional paranoid
who's given Scotland Yard

422
00:24:08,467 --> 00:24:11,129
information
that only the killer
could possibly know.

423
00:24:11,970 --> 00:24:13,767
He's led the police
to two additional bodies

424
00:24:13,839 --> 00:24:17,673
and his DNA
and a fingerprint
they found check out.

425
00:24:18,777 --> 00:24:21,007
I know
this puts a crimp
in your scoop,

426
00:24:21,847 --> 00:24:24,611
but Henry Banks is
the Tarot Card Serial Killer.

427
00:24:25,516 --> 00:24:27,006
Not Lord Lyman's son.

428
00:24:29,720 --> 00:24:31,517
Well, I can't say
I'm not walking on air.

429
00:24:32,423 --> 00:24:35,620
Oh, Jesus, If I ever catch
that Joe Strombel,
I'll kill him.

430
00:24:35,693 --> 00:24:37,684
I only hope
Peter forgives me
for what I've done.

431
00:24:37,761 --> 00:24:38,853
For what?

432
00:24:38,929 --> 00:24:40,863
I lied to him.
I'm not Jade Spence.

433
00:24:40,931 --> 00:24:44,367
I'm a pushy,
duplicitous, ambitious
college student.

434
00:24:44,435 --> 00:24:45,424
I lied to him,
over and over.

435
00:24:45,536 --> 00:24:47,868
Darling, he lied to you, too,
so it's even.

436
00:24:47,938 --> 00:24:51,339
His lies pale in comparison
to the enormity
of what I've done.

437
00:24:51,842 --> 00:24:54,902
So marry him
as Jade Spence.
Don't tell him.

438
00:24:54,979 --> 00:24:58,312
You know,
you don't have to be
Sondra Pransky ever again.

439
00:24:58,382 --> 00:24:59,815
Marry him as Jade Spence.

440
00:24:59,884 --> 00:25:02,909
Yeah, but I don't want to
have to get you a
Father's Day gift every year.

441
00:25:03,253 --> 00:25:07,883
You know, I don't know how to
break this to you, honey,
but you were adopted. Okay?

442
00:25:07,957 --> 00:25:09,891
Your mother and I,
we were at the orphanage,

443
00:25:09,959 --> 00:25:12,257
we wanted
a handicapped child, and...

444
00:25:12,996 --> 00:25:15,658
Ah, finally.
Just you and I all weekend.

445
00:25:15,798 --> 00:25:16,787
Yeah.

446
00:25:18,701 --> 00:25:20,259
I thought you'd like it here.

447
00:25:20,470 --> 00:25:21,801
It's lovely.
Mmm-hmm.

448
00:25:24,407 --> 00:25:26,068
Peter?
Yes.

449
00:25:26,142 --> 00:25:28,667
I have
a confession to make.
Oh, God, so do I.

450
00:25:29,178 --> 00:25:31,169
Oh, well, let me go first.

451
00:25:31,247 --> 00:25:33,147
Actually, no,
let me, please,

452
00:25:33,216 --> 00:25:34,513
because mine's
been bothering me all day.

453
00:25:34,617 --> 00:25:35,948
I just want
to get it off my chest.

454
00:25:36,019 --> 00:25:39,784
When I told you I was
going away for a few days
on business,

455
00:25:39,922 --> 00:25:42,254
I was lying.

456
00:25:43,091 --> 00:25:45,082
I know.
You know? How?

457
00:25:45,761 --> 00:25:47,820
Oh, I saw you.
You saw me? No.

458
00:25:48,163 --> 00:25:50,563
I was at dinner, and...
With your father?

459
00:25:50,999 --> 00:25:54,196
Actually...
Well, anyway,
it doesn't matter. Really.

460
00:25:54,570 --> 00:25:58,472
The truth is,
that a company my father owns

461
00:25:58,540 --> 00:26:00,201
is about to merge
with a company
in the Middle East.

462
00:26:00,275 --> 00:26:02,243
It's a very
sensitive situation,

463
00:26:02,311 --> 00:26:04,006
and the less
anyone knows about it,
the better.

464
00:26:04,079 --> 00:26:05,671
And we just didn't want
the press to sniff it out.

465
00:26:05,747 --> 00:26:06,941
I mean,
that's no excuse, really.

466
00:26:07,015 --> 00:26:09,347
I'm just very sorry
for the extreme secrecy.

467
00:26:09,418 --> 00:26:12,478
No, no, no, it's fine.
I'm glad.

468
00:26:12,554 --> 00:26:16,285
It's your own
secret information.
That's fine.

469
00:26:16,358 --> 00:26:18,621
So your father took you out
for a birthday dinner

470
00:26:18,693 --> 00:26:20,388
and you saw me.
